The trade turnover between the two countries grew exponentially and by 2014 Moldova had become the country with the highest trade deficit in the world, which was equal to 64.2% of the GDP.
This grotesque trade deficit triggers some questions: Why has Moldova chosen to export labor power and imports fossil energy from Russia? What implications did this political dependency have for the country? “To sustain its model of modernization its dependent economies must account for their own energy needs through imports from the core which is facilitated by development of bilateral trade relations (Markell, 1994).” (Howson, 2002) On the one hand, the energy-intensive industrial development model implies reducing taxes and developing an international free trade zone, and on the other hand, it guarantees the availability of unlimited supplies of fossil fuel energy integrated into the global energy market. Therefore, the economic development of Moldova’s economy is considered to depend on Russia as an energy supplier.
